1. echo - Print text on the terminal
What it does

Displays text or variables on the screen.

Syntax
echo "text"
Examples
echo "Hello World"

echo $HOME

echo "My name is John"
Useful Options
echo -n "Hello"     # Don't print new line

echo -e "Hello\nWorld"   # Interpret escape characters
Memory Trick

echo = say something loudly

Just like your voice echoes, this command prints text.

2. whoami - Show current user
What it does

Displays the username of the currently logged-in user.

Syntax
whoami
Example
whoami

Output:

john
Memory Trick

who am I ?

Exactly what the command asks.

3. id - Show user and group information
What it does

Displays:

User ID (UID)
Group ID (GID)
Groups the user belongs to
Syntax
id
Example
id

Output:

uid=1000(john) gid=1000(john) groups=1000(john),27(sudo)
Useful Options
id -u     # Show only user ID

id -g     # Show only group ID

id -un    # Show username

id -gn    # Show group name
Memory Trick

id = identity

Shows your Linux identity card.

4. id -un - Show username only
What it does

Displays only the username.

Syntax
id -un
Example
id -un

Output:

john
Break it down
-u   User ID

-n   Name instead of number
Memory Trick

u = user

n = name

5. cd - Change directory
What it does

Moves you from one directory to another.

Syntax
cd directory_name
Examples

Move into folder:

cd Documents

Move back one folder:

cd ..

Go to home:

cd

# OR

cd ~

Go to root:

cd /

Go to previous directory:

cd -
Memory Trick

cd = Change Directory

6. pwd - Print working directory
What it does

Shows your current location.

Syntax
pwd
Example
pwd

Output:

/home/john/Documents
Memory Trick

pwd = Present Working Directory

Where are you currently working?

7. touch - Create empty files
What it does

Creates a new empty file.

Syntax
touch filename
Examples

Create one file:

touch file.txt

Create multiple files:

touch a.txt b.txt c.txt

Create files with numbers:

touch file{1..5}.txt

Output:

file1.txt
file2.txt
file3.txt
file4.txt
file5.txt
Memory Trick

touch = touch a file into existence

8. mkdir - Make directory
What it does

Creates folders.

Syntax
mkdir folder_name
Examples

Create one folder:

mkdir Projects

Create multiple folders:

mkdir dir1 dir2 dir3

Create nested folders:

mkdir -p web/html/css
Useful Option
-p

Creates parent directories automatically.

Memory Trick

mk = make

dir = directory

mkdir = make directory

9. ls - List files and directories
What it does

Shows files and folders.

Syntax
ls
Most Useful Options
ls -l

Long listing.

ls -a

Show hidden files.

ls -lh

Human readable sizes.

ls -la

Long listing + hidden files.

ls -ltr

Sort by time, oldest first.

ls -R

Recursive listing.

Memory Trick

ls = list

10. cp - Copy files and directories
What it does

Copies files or folders.

Syntax
cp source destination
Examples

Copy file:

cp file1.txt file2.txt

Copy file to folder:

cp file.txt Documents/

Copy folder:

cp -r Folder Backup
Useful Options
-r     Recursive copy

-i     Ask before overwrite

-v     Verbose mode
Memory Trick

cp = copy

11. mv - Move or rename files
What it does

Moves files or renames them.

Syntax
mv source destination
Examples

Rename:

mv old.txt new.txt

Move file:

mv file.txt Documents/

Move multiple files:

mv *.txt Backup/
Useful Options
mv -i

mv -v
Memory Trick

mv = move

One command for both moving and renaming.

12. rm - Remove files
What it does

Deletes files and directories.

Syntax
rm filename
Examples

Delete file:

rm file.txt

Delete multiple files:

rm a.txt b.txt

Delete folder recursively:

rm -r Folder

Force delete:

rm -rf Folder
Useful Options
-r     Recursive delete

-f     Force delete

-i     Ask before deleting

-v     Verbose
⚠️ Warning
rm -rf /

Never run this command.

It attempts to delete the entire filesystem.

Memory Trick

rm = remove

13. rmdir - Remove empty directories
What it does

Deletes only empty folders.

Syntax
rmdir folder_name
Example
rmdir Test

Delete nested empty folders:

rmdir -p a/b/c
Memory Trick

rmdir = remove directory

Only works if the directory is empty.

